\b \cf0 The OT-as-predisposition thesis
\b0  is actually quite sophisticated. You're essentially reading the Old Testament as a 
\b pedagogical trap
\b0  \'97 not in a cynical sense, but in a structurally intentional one. The violence, the contradictions, the impossible demands, the cycles of failure \'97 they don't resolve 
\i within
\i0  the OT framework. They accumulate pressure. The reader who engages seriously enough hits a wall that the text itself cannot climb over. The NT then arrives not as a 
\i sequel
\i0  but as a 
\b pressure release valve that was always the architectural destination
\b0 .\
That's a more interesting reading than either fundamentalism ("it all coheres literally") or liberal dismissal ("the OT God is just primitive"). You're describing a 
\i designed tension
\i0  \'97 which interestingly aligns with how Paul explicitly frames the Torah in Galatians: the law as 
\i paidagogos
\i0 , a custodian or tutor whose job is specifically to lead toward something it cannot itself provide.\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf4 \strokec4 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\b \cf0 \strokec2 The WWI/WWII 
\f3 \strokec2 \uc0\u8594 
\f0 \strokec2  pacifism 
\f3 \strokec2 \uc0\u8594 
\f0 \strokec2  Hiroshima ratchet is where your observation gets genuinely original.
