\ls8\ilvl0
\b \cf0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	1	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 WWI/WWII
\b0  \'97 industrial-scale killing so vast and so morally disorienting that it produces a genuine civilizational trauma response\
\ls8\ilvl0
\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	2	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Trauma response
\b0  \'97 a reaching for the broader "kill = forbidden" translation, not as careful scholarship but as 
\b moral self-protection
\b0 . Pacifism as psychological refuge from an unbearable reality\
\ls8\ilvl0
\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	3	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 The Hiroshima counter-move
\b0  \'97 which is almost 
\i exactly
\i0  the Augustinian/dispensationalist escape route, now operating at the level of geopolitics rather than theology: "this killing was 
\i necessary
\i0 , 
\i authorized
\i0 , 
\i proportionate
\i0  \'97 therefore it falls outside the forbidden category"\
\ls8\ilvl0\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	4	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 The ratchet clicks \'97 because now you've established a 
\b secular framework
\b0  that mirrors the OT distinction between 
\i ratsach
\i0  and 
\i harag
\i0 , except without the theological scaffolding that gave those distinctions their grounding\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0
\cf0 \strokec2 What makes the Hiroshima case so linguistically and morally vertiginous is that the Americans who made and defended that decision were overwhelmingly 
\b Christian
\b0 , many from traditions using the "kill = forbidden" translation \'97 and yet they performed precisely the 
\i ratsach/harag
\i0  distinction that translation was meant to collapse. They intuitively knew the difference between murder and killing, applied it, but were operating within a translation tradition that officially denied the distinction existed.\
That's not hypocrisy exactly \'97 it's the 
\b distinction reasserting itself through behavior even when the language had obscured it
\b0 .\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf4 \strokec4 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\b \cf0 \strokec2 The deeper pattern you're pointing at
\b0  is that the 
\i ratsach/harag
\i0  distinction is not merely a Hebrew philological curiosity. It seems to be a 
\b cognitively universal category
\b0  that keeps resurging regardless of how language or theology tries to flatten it. Every civilization, in every era, under sufficient pressure, reconstructs some version of:\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-500\partightenfactor0
\ls9\ilvl0
\i \cf0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 There is killing that is murder
