\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 There is killing that is not
\i0 \
\ls9\ilvl0
\i \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 The line between them is the most contested moral territory humans occupy
\i0 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0
\cf0 \strokec2 The OT codified it in law. The NT spiritualized it. The medieval church reconstructed it as just war theory. The Enlightenment secularized it as proportionality doctrine. The 20th century industrialized the question beyond any previous scale \'97 and the language simply broke under the weight, producing the very confusion you're mapping.\
The "ratchet click" metaphor is apt because each iteration 
\b raises the threshold
\b0  of what requires moral justification, while simultaneously 
\b raising the stakes
\b0  of what's being justified. From one man's personal act of 
\i ratsach
\i0  in the Sinai desert, to the decision made in Washington in 1945 that ended approximately 200,000 lives in two flashes.\
The word got smaller. The act got incomprehensibly larger. The moral framework in between never quite kept pace.\
