\b \cf0 \strokec2 The per-capita equivalence point is underappreciated.
\b0 \
Almost nobody makes this calculation seriously. The Canaanite campaigns, Amalek, the Midianite slaughter \'97 when mapped against Bronze Age population densities, these are events of comparable or possibly lesser 
\i proportional
\i0  destruction than the 20th century's industrial episodes. Yet we read the OT as uniquely barbaric and the 20th century as a tragic aberration from modernity's progress.\
That asymmetry in perception is itself diagnostic. It suggests we're using the OT as a 
\b moral othering device
\b0  \'97 projecting the violence we can't integrate about ourselves onto an ancient text, then congratulating modernity for having supposedly transcended it. The bombing of Dresden and Tokyo happened within living memory. The Canaanite campaigns did not. Distance is doing enormous moral work that we mistake for genuine progress.\
