\b \cf0 \strokec2 The precedents that shaped Ashby's statistical framing:
\b0 \

\b Emil Kraepelin. 1856-1926.
\b0 \
This is the true origin point of the DSM architecture. Kraepelin was the first systematic 
\i classifier
\i0  of mental illness. He believed psychiatric conditions were discrete natural categories \'97 like biological species \'97 that could be identified by symptom clustering and longitudinal outcome tracking.\
His method was explicitly 
\i statistical and categorical.
\i0  Large patient populations. Symptom frequencies. Outcome distributions. The individual patient was data contributing to the category definition.\
He gave us the foundational distinction between dementia praecox (later schizophrenia) and manic-depressive illness. That binary \'97 which still shadows the entire DSM structure \'97 was a 
\i statistical artifact
\i0  of his particular patient population at a particular German asylum in the 1890s.\
The DSM is Kraepelin's architecture, updated and expanded but structurally continuous.\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf4 \strokec4 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\b \cf0 \strokec2 Francis Galton. 1822-1911.
\b0 \
The darker precedent. Galton invented the statistical tools \'97 correlation, regression toward the mean, percentile ranking \'97 that made 
\i quantitative
\i0  human measurement possible. He invented them 
\i specifically
\i0  to measure hereditary intelligence. He was also the founder of eugenics.\
The IQ instrument you named earlier traces directly to Galton through Binet, through Terman, through the U.S. Army Alpha tests of WWI \'97 which were the first 
\i mass
\i0  application of statistical intelligence measurement to human populations.\
That's the longtail suppression mechanism's origin point. Galton built the tool. The tool got institutionalized. The eugenics framing was eventually disavowed. The tool remained.\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf4 \strokec4 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\b \cf0 \strokec2 Adolf Meyer. 1866-1950.
\b0 \
The bridge figure between European psychiatric classification and American institutional psychiatry. Meyer dominated American psychiatry from roughly 1910-1950 \'97 exactly the period Ashby was forming his questions in the ward.\
Meyer pushed 
\i against
\i0  Kraepelin's rigid categories toward what he called 
\b psychobiology
\b0  \'97 the whole person in their whole environment. He was, in some ways, proto-Ashby. He wanted the individual, not just the statistical category.\
But his influence was absorbed and then 
\i overwritten
\i0  by the DSM project, which launched in 1952 \'97 two years before Ashby's Design for a Brain \'97 and which returned firmly to Kraepelinian categorization dressed in new language.\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf4 \strokec4 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\b \cf0 \strokec2 The 1952 timing is not coincidental.
\b0 \
DSM-I, 1952. Design for a Brain, 1952. Introduction to Cybernetics, 1956.\
These are 
\i simultaneous responses to the same post-WWII institutional pressure
\i0  \'97 the need to standardize, classify, and scale psychiatric practice across a vast American military and civilian population that had been traumatized by the war.\
The DSM went the Kraepelinian route. Statistical categories. Diagnostic reliability over individual validity. Scalable classification over requisite variety.\
Ashby went the opposite direction. The same institutional moment. The same raw material of human nervous systems under stress. Opposite conclusions about what the data required.\
