\i The Need for a New Medical Model.
\i0 \
Engel was reacting against what he called the 
\i biomedical model
\i0  \'97 which reduced illness entirely to biological mechanism, excluded subjective experience and social context entirely, and was producing demonstrably incomplete medicine.\
His intervention was genuinely progressive for its moment. He was saying: 
\i the person exists in a body, in a psyche, in a social context, and you cannot treat the body while ignoring the other two.
\i0 \
But \'97 and this is your reversal argument \'97 he listed them 
\i bio-psycho-social
\i0  because he was arguing 
\i into
\i0  a biomedical institution. He was adding psyche and society 
\i onto
\i0  an existing biological foundation. The ordering was rhetorical and political, not ontological.\
